<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Coverlet configuration for tests/MTConnect.NET-Integration-Tests only.

  This is tests/coverlet.runsettings verbatim, plus two product
  assemblies added to the Exclude list. It is applied solely to the
  integration test project (CI runs that project as its own
  `dotnet test` step with this file passed via the settings flag; the
  solution-wide run that uses tests/coverlet.runsettings no longer
  runs this project). Every other test project keeps the shared
  tests/coverlet.runsettings unchanged.

  Why the extra exclusions:
    MTConnect.NET-Integration-Tests.ClientAgentCommunicationTests
    drives the in-process Agent broker + embedded HTTP server + HTTP
    streaming client + SHDR adapter as a single timing-critical
    sample-delivery hot path. Under coverlet IL instrumentation that
    hot path is slowed enough that, on a slow shared 2-CPU CI runner,
    a Sample observation arrives after the test's 30000 ms assertion
    wait elapses (no HTTP stream timeout: the stream stays alive; the
    sample is merely late).

    Two of the assemblies on that path are also covered, faster, by
    dedicated unit suites under the shared runsettings, so dropping
    their instrumentation here loses no net (merged) coverage:

    - [MTConnect.NET-Common]*  MTConnectAgentBroker observation
      buffering / sequence / delivery. By far the largest product
      assembly (all regenerated device / asset / observation types),
      so it is the dominant IL-instrumentation cost on this host.
      Covered by the 33-file MTConnect.NET-Common-Tests suite and,
      end to end, by MTConnect.NET-HTTP-Tests, which starts a real
      MTConnectAgentBroker via AgentRunner
      (tests/MTConnect.NET-Tests-Agents/AgentRunner.cs).
    - [MTConnect.NET-HTTP]*    embedded HTTP server stream + HTTP
      streaming client per-chunk hot loop. Covered end to end by
      MTConnect.NET-HTTP-Tests: AgentRunner spins up the real
      MTConnectHttpServer and the suite streams Current / Sample
      through MTConnectHttpClient / MTConnectHttpSampleClient
      (Clients/SampleStream.cs, Clients/Sample.cs) against it.

    MTConnect.NET-SHDR is deliberately NOT excluded: AgentRunner feeds
    the broker directly and does not exercise the SHDR adapter, and
    MTConnect.NET-SHDR-Tests covers only SHDR data-item
    formatting/parsing (DataItems.cs), so the integration suite is the
    only runtime coverage of ShdrIntervalAdapter / ShdrAdapterClient
    (the TCP adapter to agent path). It is also a small assembly whose
    instrumentation is not the dominant cost, so it stays instrumented
    to preserve that unique, non-redundant coverage.

    The integration suite remains a full behavioural end-to-end test;
    only its (redundant) coverage of MTConnect.NET-Common and
    MTConnect.NET-HTTP is dropped, and those lines are still collected
    at equal-or-greater fidelity by the faster suites whose Cobertura
    ReportGenerator merges alongside this one.

  Everything else (format, include/exclude of test assemblies,
  ExcludeByFile, ExcludeByAttribute, MaxCpuCount=1 for cross-assembly
  VSTest-host serialisation) is identical to tests/coverlet.runsettings
  so the only behavioural difference is the narrowed instrumentation
  surface for this one project.
-->
<RunSettings>
    <RunConfiguration>
        <MaxCpuCount>1</MaxCpuCount>
    </RunConfiguration>
    <DataCollectionRunSettings>
        <DataCollectors>
            <DataCollector friendlyName="XPlat code coverage">
                <Configuration>
                    <Format>cobertura</Format>
                    <Include>[MTConnect.NET-*]*</Include>
                    <Exclude>[MTConnect.NET-*-Tests]*,[MTConnect.NET-*-Tests.*]*,[MTConnect.NET-Common]*,[MTConnect.NET-HTTP]*</Exclude>
                    <ExcludeByFile>**/*.g.cs.bak,**/TestHelpers/**/*.cs,**/TestDoubles/**/*.cs</ExcludeByFile>
                    <ExcludeByAttribute>Obsolete,GeneratedCodeAttribute,CompilerGeneratedAttribute,ExcludeFromCodeCoverageAttribute</ExcludeByAttribute>
                    <SingleHit>false</SingleHit>
                    <UseSourceLink>true</UseSourceLink>
                    <IncludeTestAssembly>false</IncludeTestAssembly>
                    <SkipAutoProps>false</SkipAutoProps>
                    <DeterministicReport>true</DeterministicReport>
                </Configuration>
            </DataCollector>
        </DataCollectors>
    </DataCollectionRunSettings>
</RunSettings>
